{"title_page": "Jonas Wood", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n'''Jonas Wood''' (born 1977) is a [[contemporary artist]] based in [[Los Angeles]].\n\n== Background ==\nRaised in Boston,<ref name=\"SSF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.artinamericamagazine.com/news-features/interviews/super-sports-fan-an-interview-with-jonas-wood/|title=Super Sports Fan: An Interview with Jonas Wood|author=Carr, Emily Leisz|date=October 9, 2013|work=[[Art in America]]|accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref> Wood is the child of \"art-inclined parents\".<ref name=\"TI\">{{cite web|url=http://tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/03/20/the-insider/|title=The Insider {{!}} Jonas Wood|author=Yablonsky, Linda|date=March 20, 2012|work=[[T: The New York Times Style Magazine|T]]|accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref> Wood grew up surrounded by his grandfather\u2019s art collection which featured works from [[Francis Bacon (artist)|Francis Bacon]], [[Alexander Calder]], [[Jim Dine]], [[Robert Motherwell]], [[Larry Rivers]], and [[Andy Warhol]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://gagosian.com/artists/jonas-wood/|title=Jonas Wood|website=Gagosian}}</ref> He graduated from the [[Cambridge School of Weston]] in 1995.<ref>{{cite web|title=CSW Alumnus Designs Floors for New Taschen Store|url=http://www.csw.org/page/News-Detail?pk=978012&fromId=212982|website=The Cambridge School of Weston|publisher=The Cambridge School of Weston|accessdate=July 10, 2015}}</ref> As an undergraduate, he chose to study at Hobart College, a [[liberal arts]] school where he could study both science and art. Wood\u2019s focus was on psychology during the majority of his time studying at Hobart and William Smith College. By his junior year, he had completed his psychology major and he spent his senior year studying painting.<ref name=\"QwAJW\">{{cite web|url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/blog/2010/02/qa-with-artist-jonas-wood/|title=Q&A with Artist Jonas Wood|date=February 16, 2010|publisher=[[Hammer Museum]]|accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref> He now holds a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[psychology]] from [[Hobart and William Smith Colleges]] in 1999 and a [[Masters of Fine Arts]] degree from [[University of Washington]] in 2002.<ref name=\"JWA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.artspace.com/jonas_wood|title=Jonas Wood|publisher=[[Artspace]]|accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref> \n\nShortly after graduating, Wood moved to Los Angeles, where he worked as a studio assistant for two years for painter [[Laura Owens]] and then another two years for sculptor [[Matt Johnson (artist)|Matt Johnson]]. <ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://depts.washington.edu/soanews/online/eblast-newsletters/october-2011/a-trio-of-artistic-trajectories/.|title=A Trio of Artistic Trajectories|website=School of Art News Events RSS}}</ref> While working as an assistant, Wood continued to make his own work. \n\n== Process ==\nDuring his student years, he explored making collage-like works based on montaged photographs that he took of himself, his friends, and their surroundings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://artsandculturetx.com/painting-toward-intimacy-jonas-wood-at-dallas-museum-of-art/|title=Painting Toward Intimacy: Jonas Wood at Dallas Museum of Art|last1=August|first1=Laura|website=Arts & Culture Texas}}</ref> Wood now paints from studies ([[collage]]s and [[drawing]]s) and sometimes uses [[photography]], but most of his works and studies are part of the larger plan of creating paintings.<ref name=\"QwAJW\" /> Wood states, \"I work from photos. I collect photos, ones I\u2019ve taken or I\u2019ve appropriated or that other people have sent to me. And then I either make a collage of those things or work directly from photos. And a bunch of times, I\u2019ll make a drawing from a found photo, a photo collage, or photo I took, and then make a painting from that drawing.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/jonas-wood-interview-1501156|title=I Was So Afraid for Way Too Long': Jonas Wood on How Going It Alone Helped Him Survive His Immense Art-Market Success|last1=Pobric|first1=Pac|website=Artnet News}}</ref> Wood has also done [[etching]]s.<ref name=\"SSF\" /> He maintains active drawing, [[printmaking]], and collage practices, each of which helps him generate techniques that he eventually uses in his paintings.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.davidkordanskygallery.com/artist/jonas-wood.|title=Jonas Wood|last1=Kordansky|first1=David|website=David Kordansky Gallery}}</ref>  \n\nWood's studio is filled with the objects that influence his work, such as his children's drawings, plants, vessels, and sport memorabilia. An example of this includes a giant basketball sculpture by [[Paa Joe]]. He also works in close proximity to his partner, Shio Kusaka, whose work he appropriates and collaborates with. Wood's influences are also auditory, as he tends to listen to basketball podcasts while he works.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/22/t-magazine/jonas-wood.html|title=An Artist on Finding Balance, and His Giant Basketball Sculpture|last1=Zara|first1=Janelle|website=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref> \n\nA [[The New York Times|New York Times]] article by Janelle Zara states, \"the studio is where Wood culls various photographs from the internet or his own archive and uses them as source material for his paintings\". The appropriated imagery is organized in labeled folders in his studio to be physically accessible during his painting process. The images are printed out and pinned onto walls, then flattened and distilled into blocks of color. Wood then layers these \"dense graphic patterns, overlapping fields of stipples and stripes, circles, squares, dots and wood grains\".<ref name=\":4\" /> \n\n== Themes ==\nJonas Wood\u2019s paintings, drawings, and prints can be described as a myriad of genres, such as domestic interiors, landscapes, still-life and sports scenes.<ref name=\"SSF\" /> Translating the three-dimensional world around him into flat color and line, he confounds expectations of scale and vantage point that reflect an instantly recognizable vision of the contemporary world.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn an ''[[Architectural Digest]]'' story by Rebecca Bates, Wood claimed to paint to create new memories of his former residences: \"I'm interested in exploring the spaces that I\u2019ve inhabited and the psychological impact they've had on me and my memories of them,...And then I can create a new memory of that space.\"<ref name=\"diges\">{{cite web|url=http://www.architecturaldigest.com/blogs/daily/2013/09/jonas-wood-mosaics-anton-kern-gallery|title=Jonas Wood at Anton Kern Gallery|author=Bates, Rebecca|date=September 12, 2013|work=[[Architectural Digest]]|accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref> The result is the perception that his work is very sincere.<ref name=\"nyt1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/12/arts/design/12gall.html|title=Art in Review|author=Johnson, Ken|date=December 11, 2008|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Style ==\nWood's style is described as multidimensional. In ''[[T: The New York Times Style Magazine|T]]'', he was described as working \"With one foot in [[Modernist]] cool and the other in vibrant [[Pop Art]]\".<ref name=\"TI\" /> Similarly, [[Artspace]] describes his work as if he works \"With one foot rooted in [[Analytic Cubism]] and the other in Contemporary [[Pop art]]\".<ref name=\"JWA\" /> In ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' Wood is described in reminiscence of classic masters: \"Although Wood pays homage to [[Vincent van Gogh|Van Gogh]] along with other abstract colorists like [[Henri Matisse|Matisse]], [[Pablo Picasso|Picasso]] and [[Keith Haring]], his works are decidedly modern... Both steeped in tradition yet completely fresh, Wood captures the impossible sharpness of modernity with the familiar feelings of home.\"<ref name=\"JWIYIHCWPI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/30/jonas-wood_n_4005422.html|title=Jonas Wood Invites You Into His Colorful, Warped Painted Interiors|author=Frank, Priscilla|date=September 30, 2013|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref> [[Roberta Smith]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' notes that \"his works negotiate an uneasy truce among the abstract, the representational, the photographic and the just plain weird.\"<ref name=\"PbJW\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/18/arts/design/paintings-by-jonas-wood-at-anton-kern-gallery-art-review.html|title=Paintings by Jonas Wood|author=Smith, Roberta|date=March 17, 2011|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nSmith compares his work to those of [[Daniel Heidkamp]].<ref name=\"nyt2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/11/arts/design/daniel-heidkamp.html|title=Daniel Heidkamp|author=Smith, Roberta|date=July 10, 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref> In another story about Wood, Smith noted that as a painter who paints his own life, his art bears similarity to [[\u00c9douard Vuillard]], [[Henri Matisse]], [[Alex Katz]] and [[David Hockney]].<ref name=PbJW />\n\n== Marriage ==\nWood currently shares a studio with artist [https://gagosian.com/artists/shio-kusaka/ Shio Kusaka], his wife since 2002. Shio Kusaka, born in Japan, creates distinctive porcelain, and Wood then photographs and paints the pieces for co-operative exhibitions. The pair often work in tandem, motifs migrating from Kusaka\u2019s ceramic vessels to Wood\u2019s paintings and back again. He and Kusaka also incorporate imagery from their expansive art collection\u2014including works by [[Alighiero Boetti]], [[Michael Frimkess]] and [[Magdalena Suarez Frimkess]], [[Mark Grotjahn]], and [[Edward Ruscha|Ed Ruscha]]\u2014as well as from their children\u2019s storybooks and drawings.<ref name=\":2\" /> They co-author art books in a series with the pen name ''Wood Kusaka Studios''.<ref name=\"hampt\">{{cite web|url=http://hamptonsarthub.com/2013/05/22/jonas-wood-shio-kusaka-still-life-with-pots-opens-may-25-at-glenn-horowitz-bookseller/|title=\"Jonas Wood & Shio Kusaka: Still Life With Pots\" opens May 25 at Glenn Horowitz Bookseller|date=May 22, 2013|publisher=Hamptons Art Hub|accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 [[Gagosian Gallery|Gagosian]] in Hong Kong presented Blackwelder, which brought together Wood\u2019s and Kusaka\u2019s works in a dedicated two-person exhibition. This was followed by the couple\u2019s first collaborative museum exhibition, at [[Museum Voorlinden]], Wassenaar, Netherlands, in 2017.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Exhibitions ==\nBlack Dragon Society was the first gallery in Los Angeles to represent his work and give him a solo exhibition in 2006. Artist [[Mark Grotjahn]] saw Wood\u2019s paintings at that show and told Anton Kern Gallery in New York City about it. The result was Anton Kern Gallery mounting a one-man exhibition for Wood during the summer of 2007, and then Shane Campbell Gallery in Chicago hosted a solo show two months later. From that point on, he has continued to exhibit his work regularly.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nPast solo exhibition have been held at at the [[Dallas Museum of Art]] (2019); Museum Voorlinden, Wassenaar, the Netherlands (with Shio Kusaka, 2017); [[Lever House]], New York (2014); and [[Hammer Museum]], Los Angeles (2010).<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nOther solo projects include Still Life with Two Owls (MOCA), the fa\u00e7ade of the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles|Museum of Contemporary Art]], Los Angeles (2016- 2018); Shelf Still Life, High Line Billboard, [[High Line Art]], New York (2014); and LAXART Billboard and Fa\u00e7ade, LAXART, Los Angeles (2014).<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nHis work is included in the permanent collections of many institutions, among them the [[Albright\u2013Knox Art Gallery|Albright-Knox Art Gallery]], Buffalo, New York; [[Centre Pompidou]], Paris; Dallas Museum of Art; Fundaci\u00f3n Jumex, Mexico City; Hammer Museum, Los Angeles; [[Marciano Art Foundation]], Los Angeles; [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], New York; Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles; [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art]]; [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]], New York; [[Broad Foundation]], Los Angeles; [[Museum of Modern Art]], New York; and [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], New York. <ref name=\":3\" /> \n\n== Bibliography ==\n*Jacob Samuel, ''Jonas Wood: Prints'', [[Gagosian]] and [[Rizzoli Libri|Rizzoli]], New York, 2019.\n*Anna Katherine Brodbeck, Ken Allan, [[Hans Ulrich Obrist]], ''Jonas Wood'', Dallas Museum of Art, 2019.\n*[[Mark Grotjahn]], [[Helen Molesworth]], Ian Alteveer, ''Jonas Wood'', [[Phaidon Press|Phaidon]], London, 2019.\n\n== References ==\n<br />{{Authority control}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wood, Jonas}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Artists from Boston]]\n[[Category:Hobart and William Smith Colleges alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Washington alumni]]\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n'''Jonas Wood''' (born 1977) is a [[contemporary artist]] based in [[Los Angeles]].\n\n== Background ==\nRaised in Boston,<ref name=\"SSF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.artinamericamagazine.com/news-features/interviews/super-sports-fan-an-interview-with-jonas-wood/|title=Super Sports Fan: An Interview with Jonas Wood|author=Carr, Emily Leisz|date=October 9, 2013|work=[[Art in America]]|accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref> Wood is the child of \"art-inclined parents\".<ref name=\"TI\">{{cite web|url=http://tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/03/20/the-insider/|title=The Insider {{!}} Jonas Wood|author=Yablonsky, Linda|date=March 20, 2012|work=[[T: The New York Times Style Magazine|T]]|accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref> Wood grew up surrounded by his grandfather\u2019s art collection which featured works from [[Francis Bacon (artist)|Francis Bacon]], [[Alexander Calder]], [[Jim Dine]], [[Robert Motherwell]], [[Larry Rivers]], and [[Andy Warhol]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://gagosian.com/artists/jonas-wood/|title=Jonas Wood|website=Gagosian}}</ref> He graduated from the [[Cambridge School of Weston]] in 1995.<ref>{{cite web|title=CSW Alumnus Designs Floors for New Taschen Store|url=http://www.csw.org/page/News-Detail?pk=978012&fromId=212982|website=The Cambridge School of Weston|publisher=The Cambridge School of Weston|accessdate=July 10, 2015}}</ref> As an undergraduate, he chose to study at Hobart College, a [[liberal arts]] school where he could study both science and art. Wood\u2019s focus was on psychology during the majority of his time studying at Hobart and William Smith College. By his junior year, he had completed his psychology major and he spent his senior year studying painting.<ref name=\"QwAJW\">{{cite web|url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/blog/2010/02/qa-with-artist-jonas-wood/|title=Q&A with Artist Jonas Wood|date=February 16, 2010|publisher=[[Hammer Museum]]|accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref> He now holds a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[psychology]] from [[Hobart and William Smith Colleges]] in 1999 and a [[Masters of Fine Arts]] degree from [[University of Washington]] in 2002.<ref name=\"JWA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.artspace.com/jonas_wood|title=Jonas Wood|publisher=[[Artspace]]|accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref> \n\nShortly after graduating, Wood moved to Los Angeles, where he worked as a studio assistant for two years for painter [[Laura Owens]] and then another two years for sculptor [[Matt Johnson (artist)|Matt Johnson]]. <ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://depts.washington.edu/soanews/online/eblast-newsletters/october-2011/a-trio-of-artistic-trajectories/.|title=A Trio of Artistic Trajectories|website=School of Art News Events RSS}}</ref> While working as an assistant, Wood continued to make his own work. \n\n== Process ==\nDuring his student years, he explored making collage-like works based on montaged photographs that he took of himself, his friends, and their surroundings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://artsandculturetx.com/painting-toward-intimacy-jonas-wood-at-dallas-museum-of-art/|title=Painting Toward Intimacy: Jonas Wood at Dallas Museum of Art|last1=August|first1=Laura|website=Arts & Culture Texas}}</ref> Wood now paints from studies ([[collage]]s and [[drawing]]s) and sometimes uses [[photography]], but most of his works and studies are part of the larger plan of creating paintings.<ref name=\"QwAJW\" /> Wood states, \"I work from photos. I collect photos, ones I\u2019ve taken or I\u2019ve appropriated or that other people have sent to me. And then I either make a collage of those things or work directly from photos. And a bunch of times, I\u2019ll make a drawing from a found photo, a photo collage, or photo I took, and then make a painting from that drawing.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/jonas-wood-interview-1501156|title=I Was So Afraid for Way Too Long': Jonas Wood on How Going It Alone Helped Him Survive His Immense Art-Market Success|last1=Pobric|first1=Pac|website=Artnet News}}</ref> Wood has also done [[etching]]s.<ref name=\"SSF\" /> He maintains active drawing, [[printmaking]], and collage practices, each of which helps him generate techniques that he eventually uses in his paintings.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.davidkordanskygallery.com/artist/jonas-wood.|title=Jonas Wood|last1=Kordansky|first1=David|website=David Kordansky Gallery}}</ref>  \n\nWood's studio is filled with the objects that influence his work, such as his children's drawings, plants, vessels, and sport memorabilia. An example of this includes a giant basketball sculpture by [[Paa Joe]]. He also works in close proximity to his partner, Shio Kusaka, whose work he appropriates and collaborates with. Wood's influences are also auditory, as he tends to listen to basketball podcasts while he works.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/22/t-magazine/jonas-wood.html|title=An Artist on Finding Balance, and His Giant Basketball Sculpture|last1=Zara|first1=Janelle|website=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref> \n\nA [[The New York Times|New York Times]] article by Janelle Zara states, \"the studio is where Wood culls various photographs from the internet or his own archive and uses them as source material for his paintings\". The appropriated imagery is organized in labeled folders in his studio to be physically accessible during his painting process. The images are printed out and pinned onto walls, then flattened and distilled into blocks of color. Wood then layers these \"dense graphic patterns, overlapping fields of stipples and stripes, circles, squares, dots and wood grains\".<ref name=\":4\" /> \n\n== Themes ==\nJonas Wood\u2019s paintings, drawings, and prints can be described as a myriad of genres, such as domestic interiors, landscapes, still-life and sports scenes.<ref name=\"SSF\" /> Translating the three-dimensional world around him into flat color and line, he confounds expectations of scale and vantage point that reflect an instantly recognizable vision of the contemporary world.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn an ''[[Architectural Digest]]'' story by Rebecca Bates, Wood claimed to paint to create new memories of his former residences: \"I'm interested in exploring the spaces that I\u2019ve inhabited and the psychological impact they've had on me and my memories of them,...And then I can create a new memory of that space.\"<ref name=\"diges\">{{cite web|url=http://www.architecturaldigest.com/blogs/daily/2013/09/jonas-wood-mosaics-anton-kern-gallery|title=Jonas Wood at Anton Kern Gallery|author=Bates, Rebecca|date=September 12, 2013|work=[[Architectural Digest]]|accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref> The result is the perception that his work is very sincere.<ref name=\"nyt1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/12/arts/design/12gall.html|title=Art in Review|author=Johnson, Ken|date=December 11, 2008|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Style ==\nWood's style is described as multidimensional. In ''[[T: The New York Times Style Magazine|T]]'', he was described as working \"With one foot in [[Modernist]] cool and the other in vibrant [[Pop Art]]\".<ref name=\"TI\" /> Similarly, [[Artspace]] describes his work as if he works \"With one foot rooted in [[Analytic Cubism]] and the other in Contemporary [[Pop art]]\".<ref name=\"JWA\" /> In ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' Wood is described in reminiscence of classic masters: \"Although Wood pays homage to [[Vincent van Gogh|Van Gogh]] along with other abstract colorists like [[Henri Matisse|Matisse]], [[Pablo Picasso|Picasso]] and [[Keith Haring]], his works are decidedly modern... Both steeped in tradition yet completely fresh, Wood captures the impossible sharpness of modernity with the familiar feelings of home.\"<ref name=\"JWIYIHCWPI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/30/jonas-wood_n_4005422.html|title=Jonas Wood Invites You Into His Colorful, Warped Painted Interiors|author=Frank, Priscilla|date=September 30, 2013|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref> [[Roberta Smith]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' notes that \"his works negotiate an uneasy truce among the abstract, the representational, the photographic and the just plain weird.\"<ref name=\"PbJW\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/18/arts/design/paintings-by-jonas-wood-at-anton-kern-gallery-art-review.html|title=Paintings by Jonas Wood|author=Smith, Roberta|date=March 17, 2011|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nSmith compares his work to those of [[Daniel Heidkamp]].<ref name=\"nyt2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/11/arts/design/daniel-heidkamp.html|title=Daniel Heidkamp|author=Smith, Roberta|date=July 10, 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref> In another story about Wood, Smith noted that as a painter who paints his own life, his art bears similarity to [[\u00c9douard Vuillard]], [[Henri Matisse]], [[Alex Katz]] and [[David Hockney]].<ref name=PbJW />\n\n== Marriage ==\nWood currently shares a studio with artist [https://gagosian.com/artists/shio-kusaka/ Shio Kusaka], his wife since 2002. Shio Kusaka, born in Japan, creates distinctive porcelain, and Wood then photographs and paints the pieces for co-operative exhibitions. The pair often work in tandem, motifs migrating from Kusaka\u2019s ceramic vessels to Wood\u2019s paintings and back again. Common subjects include plants, portraits, and sports imagery, all of which come together in Wood\u2019s lush interiors and intricate still lifes. He and Kusaka also incorporate imagery from their expansive art collection\u2014including works by [[Alighiero Boetti]], [[Michael Frimkess]] and [[Magdalena Suarez Frimkess]], [[Mark Grotjahn]], and [[Edward Ruscha|Ed Ruscha]]\u2014as well as from their children\u2019s storybooks and drawings.<ref name=\":2\" /> They co-author art books in a series with the pen name ''Wood Kusaka Studios''.<ref name=\"hampt\">{{cite web|url=http://hamptonsarthub.com/2013/05/22/jonas-wood-shio-kusaka-still-life-with-pots-opens-may-25-at-glenn-horowitz-bookseller/|title=\"Jonas Wood & Shio Kusaka: Still Life With Pots\" opens May 25 at Glenn Horowitz Bookseller|date=May 22, 2013|publisher=Hamptons Art Hub|accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 [[Gagosian Gallery|Gagosian]] in Hong Kong presented Blackwelder, which brought together Wood\u2019s and Kusaka\u2019s works in a dedicated two-person exhibition. This was followed by the couple\u2019s first collaborative museum exhibition, at [[Museum Voorlinden]], Wassenaar, Netherlands, in 2017.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Exhibitions ==\nBlack Dragon Society was the first gallery in Los Angeles to represent his work and give him a solo exhibition in 2006. Artist [[Mark Grotjahn]] saw Wood\u2019s paintings at that show and told Anton Kern Gallery in New York City about it. The result was Anton Kern Gallery mounting a one-man exhibition for Wood during the summer of 2007, and then Shane Campbell Gallery in Chicago hosted a solo show two months later. From that point on, he has continued to exhibit his work regularly.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nPast solo exhibition have been held at at the [[Dallas Museum of Art]] (2019); Museum Voorlinden, Wassenaar, the Netherlands (with Shio Kusaka, 2017); [[Lever House]], New York (2014); and [[Hammer Museum]], Los Angeles (2010).<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nOther solo projects include Still Life with Two Owls (MOCA), the fa\u00e7ade of the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles|Museum of Contemporary Art]], Los Angeles (2016- 2018); Shelf Still Life, High Line Billboard, [[High Line Art]], New York (2014); and LAXART Billboard and Fa\u00e7ade, LAXART, Los Angeles (2014).<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nHis work is included in the permanent collections of many institutions, among them the [[Albright\u2013Knox Art Gallery|Albright-Knox Art Gallery]], Buffalo, New York; [[Centre Pompidou]], Paris; Dallas Museum of Art; Fundaci\u00f3n Jumex, Mexico City; Hammer Museum, Los Angeles; [[Marciano Art Foundation]], Los Angeles; [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], New York; Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles; [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art]]; [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]], New York; [[Broad Foundation]], Los Angeles; [[Museum of Modern Art]], New York; and [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], New York. <ref name=\":3\" /> \n\n== Bibliography ==\n*Jacob Samuel, ''Jonas Wood: Prints'', [[Gagosian]] and [[Rizzoli Libri|Rizzoli]], New York, 2019.\n*Anna Katherine Brodbeck, Ken Allan, [[Hans Ulrich Obrist]], ''Jonas Wood'', Dallas Museum of Art, 2019.\n*[[Mark Grotjahn]], [[Helen Molesworth]], Ian Alteveer, ''Jonas Wood'', [[Phaidon Press|Phaidon]], London, 2019.\n\n== References ==\n<br 